<DOC><DOCNO> AP890105-0091 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1137EST</FILEID><FIRST>d a PM-BRF--LonelyFlight     01-05 0130</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Lonely Flight,0133</SECOND><HEAD>Subsidized Route Averages One Passenger</HEAD><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government spent $379,000 last year tosubsidize flights between Atlanta and Moultrie that averaged onepassenger.   The Department of Transportation is trying to stop the subsidy toEastern Atlantis Express' service connecting the southern Georgiacity with Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport.   The flight, with two pilots, makes two trips each way, six days aweek, but sold just 1,301 tickets, at $79 one way, last year.   David Howard, a vice president of the commuter airline, which isaffiliated with Eastern Airlines, said the route will be eliminatedif the subsidy ends.   The airline is required by law to maintain the route in exchangefor the subsidy, a carryover from the days when the governmentregulated domestic routes.</TEXT></DOC>